WOTE WORKERS WORLD PARTY?

Deirdre Griswold for President

Deirdre Griswold is a founding member of Workers World
Party and editor of Workers World newspaper. She has been a
trade unionist and anti-war activist, and has represented Workers
World Party internationally.

Deirdre went to Monroe, North Carolina in 1961 to help the
besieged Black community there which was upholding the right of
self-defense against racist night-riders. She organized and spoke
in support of the Cuban Revolution in the tense period of the Bay
of Pigs invasion. Beginning with 1962, when she helped organize
the first demonstration in the U.S. against the Viet Nam war she
was in the forefront of the anti-war struggle. She traveled to
Europe in 1965 to open contacts with the Vietnamese freedom
fighters; she worked for six months on the International War
Crimes Tribunal in 1967, which met in Stockholm and indicted
the U.S. government for war crimes in Southeast Asia.

She has written several pamphlets, including the most extensive
ﬁrst-hand reporting by any American on the unfolding revolution
in Ethiopia.

Larry Holmes for Vice President

Larry Holmes, a member of the National Committee of
Workers World Party, is well-known on the East Coast as an
anti-racist activist and is a veteran of the struggles of the seventies.

Larry resisted the Viet Nam war while inside the Army. After
being discharged because of his organizing work for the American
Servicemen’s Union, he helped build the 1973 March on
Washington of Vietnam-era vets demanding jobs and decent ben-
efits.

Larry was a key organizer of the December 1974 National
March Against Racism of 25,000 in Boston. And in 1978 he was a
national mobilizer for the historic march of 35 ,000 for affirmative
action and against the Bakke Decision in Washington. Larry
further explained the need for affirmative action in a pamphlet on
the Weber case.

As a community organizer, Larry led the successful struggle to
save the treasures of Black history in Harlem’s Schomburg
Library, winning a new building for the collection.

Larry Holmes has played a very active role in the Coalition of
Black Trade Unionists. He is also a frequent contributor to
Workers World newspaper. Labor Donated

For a working class
alternative

Poor and working people urgently need real political represen-
tation. They need a multinational workers’ party representing
Black, Latin, Asian, Native and white, that will put forward
policies and plans of action to combat the unemployment, inﬂa-
tion, cutbacks, Pentagon war threats, the rise of racism, the crisis
of the youth, and the many other urgent problems facing us.

$5,000-a-plate crowd

For Democrats and Republicans to speak for us is a fraud. They
represent the $5 ,O0O-a—plate dinner crowd. Their money comes
from Wall Street fat cats. Their orders come from corporate board
rooms. High-priced big business lobbyists fill their offices every
day. At election time they may talk “pro-labor’ ’ and speak for the
“little people.” But their real masters live off the “little people, ”
the workers and the poor.

Don’t waste your vote

In the 1980 election, no worker Black or white, should have to
waste their vote on some “lesser-evil” politician like multi-
millionaire Kennedy, who sponsored the repressive, strike-
breaking S-1 bill and who is sitting on his hands while Boston
racists in his home state beat and shoot Black school children.

WWP: 20 years of struggle

In 1980 you can vote for a party that has a program for the great
majority of the people in this country and also has a record of 20
years of struggle on their behalf. We have fought the Klan in
Virginia and Alabama, the Nazis in Milwaukee and Chicago, and
ROAR in Boston. We have fought the the auto bosses in Detroit
and the steel barons in Buffalo. We have defended prisoners in
Attica and undocumented workers in Texas. We have fought for
rent control in Baltimore and an end to heat cutoffs in Rochester.
We have defended the Patriotic Front, the Sandinistas, the Cuban
Revolution and all the socialist countries. Workers World Party
was in the forefront of the anti-Viet Nam war movement.

 

 

Fight back against
the economic crisis

The capitalist profit system is in deep crisis. But poor and
working people, as well as a large section of the middle class, are
paying the price; wage earners, the unemployed, the elderly, the
sick, the youth, mothers and children on welfare. The only way to
end this terrible situation is to rely on our own strength and
organization. We need a revived rank-and-file labor movement in
alliance with community organizations across the country to open
up a genuine struggle against inﬂation, layoffs and cutbacks.

Big business politicians make noise about oil company profits
but do nothing. WWP says the people should take over the oil
companies and run them for human need and not for profit.

Prices and profits soar while real wages drop. WWP says a
labor—community-consumer alliance can launch a fight for a
national price rollback by the corporations.

Employers lay off millions while millions more are forced to
work overtime. We say end forced overtime, shorten the work
week with no cut in pay. Low wages and cuts in benefits bring on
recessions. Raise the minimum wage and all beneﬁts to the
poor. Cut back profits. Full benefits for all the unemployed.

Bosses, like Chrysler, close down plants and lay off workers.
We say if the bosses won’t run the plants, the workers should.
No layoffs.

The nuclear industry puts profits before safety. WWP says the
people should take over the nuclear plants and shut them
down, and keep them shut until it is proven they can be run safely.

We can win these demands and many more through united
struggle. Labor must organize the unemployed, the unorga-
nized, the millions of undocumented, and build a mighty
alliance of all poor and working people. We are the millions; the
rich are a tiny minority. We can take our fate into our own
hands.

