and raising prices. We want to help these struggling people get
free, not hold them down. We won’t fight for the oil companies
profits!

WWP says that the security of poor and working people is
not threatened by the socialist countries—not by Cuba,
Viet Nam, north Korea, the USSR, Angola or any other. The
bosses hate these countries because they have gotten rid of
profiteering exploiters. That is a great victory for the peoples of
those countries. They are not our enemies. Our enemies are
Exxon, Chase Manhattan, Chrysler, and the budget cutters
and militarists in Washington who take their orders. Fight the
real enemy at home!

  

  

The problem
is capitalism-
the solution is socialism

The last 75 years of U.S. history have been a continuous cycle
of war, boom, bust, and back to war. Not one decade has passed
without a crisis or a wan. The human cost of the present inﬂa-
tion/unemployment is enormous.

Why does it happen? Because crisis for poor and working
people is built into the system.

On the one hand, 500 super-rich corporations control 95% of all
industrial and financial wealth in the country. On the other hand,
100 million workers (if they are fortunate enough to have jobs) go

a to work every day and produce the entire wealth of society. But

    

this wealth passes directly into the hands of the bosses while we
come home with a deﬂated paycheck.

Profits first. . .

The employers live by one law—maximize profits! And they
take advantage of their situation to set the lowest possible wages
and the highest possible prices. Sooner or later the gap between
what workers earn and the value they produce grows so large that
goods begin to pile up, the bosses slow down production, we get
laid off, and things just get worse.

. . .Peop|e’s needs last

Furthermore, the bosses will produce what makes the most
proﬁt, regardless of social need. If bombs bring more profit than
houses, then they make more bombs and fewer houses. A boss
would rather see people go cold or hungry than sell at a price that
would lower his proﬁt. That is why agribusiness destroys cattle
and grain, and why the oil companies would rather see people
freeze in the winter than put cheap fuel on the market.

Andwhen things get really bad, the capitalists begin to look for
war as a way out. That is why they need cops, courts, prisons, the
military, racism, and fascism to keep people down.

Let’s take it over

The way out of this situation is to get rid of the private
ownership of industry and agriculture by a class of greedy
millionaires and billionaires. The people must take it over and run

 

it in a planned way to meet the needs of the vast majority. Let us
decide how to use our own labor. Let us produce what we need,
when we need it, under safe and healthy conditions without fear of
layoffs. And let us distribute those goods among the people at
prices we can afford.

Without the bosses, without the profit system, all this can be
done with ease. We do not need the owners. They contribute
nothing to production but their anti-human policies. We make
everything run anyway. No one should have to go hungry or be
without a job or live in dilapidated housing once the poor and
working people take over. To sum it up, we need socialism.

Workers World Party intends to bring this message to the
rnillions—in this election campaign, and in a hundred and one
day-to—day struggles. It intends to expose the lies of the capitalist
politicians while it fights the capitalist bosses themselves.

